these are mostly notes for myself to keep track of everything, but they explain how TUI works
this is a little project designed just for headless linux debian on my 2018 chromebook, which is now named Walter
Walter has an intel celeron n3050 i think, 4gb of ram, 32gb storage
This project will hopefully evolve from just a library into a terminal desktop ui for Walter

Here's a little overview of how it works as of July 7, 2026
keep in mind that the init function turns off stdin blocking, stdout canonical mode, and stdout echo mode
the closeTUI function frees all buffers created internally as well as someother stuff, basically all internal varaibles
closeTUI also turns blocking back on, as well as echo and canonical mode, so definitely call closeTUI
unless you want a huge memory leak
There are multiple pixel/frame buffers, each is (SCREENWIDTH * SCREENHEIGHT) * 3 bytes and they are stored on the heap
each is made of 'Cell's, each cell is 3 bytes, one for the character, one for fg color, one for bg color, THIS IS SUBJECT TO CHANGE
There is a back buffer which is edited with back buffer commands but is hidden from the user
There is a front buffer which can be written to the screen by the user, but again its contents are generally hidden
I say they're hidden but since theyre on the heap their ADDRESSES are not in the scope of the user, but i could just make a function
	that returns their addresses if i want, i probably will tbh, so theyre not REALLY hidden
the front buffer is designed to keep track of the state of the screen itself
the back buffer is designed to be edited and then flashed to the front buffer before drawing the front buffer
There are also windows, each one with a TUIWindow id, TUIWindow is just an unsigned 8 bit integer (0-255) id
There is a wManager object, also hidden from the user, it keeps track of the active window, how many windows there are
	and an array of windowObject objects, each having x, y, width, height, and a Cell* windowBuffer
so each window also gets a framebuffer, and each is the same size as the front and back buffers that way windows can be
	resized. these buffers keep track of the state of every cell inside the window, including the borders
window buffers use local coordinates, so the top left corner of the window is always stored at windowBuffer[0]
window buffers can be flashed onto the back buffer, and their local coordinates are automatically translated to screen
	coordinates
each buffer on Walter takes up about 24kb but this number will go up when I add more color support and unicode/utf-8 support
RIGHT NOW THERE ARE ONLY SINGLE BYTE ASCII CHARACTERS SUPPORTED :(
the maximum number of windows is defined in tui.h so thats pretty easy to change, it's like 5 or something, not that it matters


